-- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an increasingly multicultural world, the relationship between language and identity remains a complicated and often fraught subject for most societies. The growing political salience of questions relating to language is evident not only in the expanded implementation of new policies and legislation, but also in heated public debates about national unity, collective identities, and the rights of linguistic minorities. By taking a comprehensive approach that considers both the inclusive and exclusive dimensions of linguistic identity across Europe and North America, the studies assembled here provide a sophisticated look at one of the global era’s defining political dynamics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aIdentity politics. 0aIntercultural communication. 0aLanguage and culturexPolitical aspects. 0aLanguage and languagesxPolitical aspects. 0aSociolinguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Historical & Comparative.2bisacsh1 aGallant, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGould, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIves, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaveau, Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraus, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeune, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatrick, Donna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt Sr., Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkenderovic, Damir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 